export const TRAVEL_VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"Four palettes, four territories.","intro":"The category defaults are rejected as primary signal: Santorini blue, resort turquoise, safari ochre, foliage red. They are not wrong — they are unearned without specific cultural grounding. Each palette is sourced from three places only — the territory's material culture, its specific light condition, and the historical pigment tradition available to the people of the place. The test is recognition: someone who has been here should know the palette without seeing the label."},"II":{"title":"Four more territories, further from the postcard.","intro":"This volume pushes harder against the category default. Tokyo is not sakura pink; Lisbon is not azulejo blue as primary; Iceland is not aurora green; Kerala is not backwater turquoise. Each is a specific hour and a specific surface — read the kicker before the swatches. As before: every swatch names its material, pigment, or light source. The hierarchy is enforced. The refuses line is part of the spec, not editorial flavour."},"III":{"title":"Four more interiors, mostly at night or under weather.","intro":"Volume III leans inward. Three of the four territories are interiors — a felt-walled ger, a Viennese kaffeehaus, an adobe house seen between mountain stops — and the fourth is a Faroese harbour so thickly fogged that it reads as an interior anyway. Light here is small, local, and almost always from below or behind. As before: every swatch names its source. The hierarchy is enforced. The refuses line names the colour that would betray the territory."}};
